 <!-- CORBA engine -->

 <refentry id="man-engine-corba">
  <refmeta>
   <refentrytitle>regina-engine-corba</refentrytitle>
   <manvolnum>1</manvolnum>
  </refmeta>

  <refnamediv>
   <refname>regina-engine-corba</refname>
   <refpurpose>&regina; &corba; calculation engine server</refpurpose>
  </refnamediv>

  <refsynopsisdiv>
   <cmdsynopsis>
    <command>regina-engine-corba</command>
    <arg><option>-ORBInitialHost</option> <replaceable>host</replaceable></arg>
    <arg><option>-ORBInitialPort</option> <replaceable>port</replaceable></arg>
    <group>
     <arg><option>-ORBpoa_iiop_name_port</option>
      <replaceable>host</replaceable></arg>
     <arg><option>-ORBpoa_iiop_name_port</option>
      <replaceable>host</replaceable><option>:</option><replaceable>port</replaceable></arg>
    </group>
   </cmdsynopsis>
  </refsynopsisdiv>

  <refsect1>
   <title>Description</title>
   <para>
    If the &regina; user interface uses &corba; to access the
    calculation engine, the calculation engine will need to be running
    as a separate server application.  This is that server application.
   </para>
   <para>
    There is no way to configure this server other than
    through the command-line options outlined above.
   </para>
   <warning>
    <para>
     Be warned that this server has <emphasis>not</emphasis> been
     audited for security!  You should <emphasis>always</emphasis>
     run this server as a guest user (such as <literal>nobody</literal>
     on &linux; systems).
    </para>
   </warning>
   <para>
    Note that this server and the user interface may be running on
    different machines.  You simply need to configure them both to refer
    to the same &corba; naming service, although read the warning below.
   </para>
   <warning>
    <para>
     By default, this engine registers itself with the naming service as
     running on machine <literal>localhost</literal>.  If the user
     interface is running on a different machine, it will take this
     information from the naming service and search for the engine on
     its own <literal>localhost</literal> which will result in an error.
    </para>
    <para>
     Thus, if you are running this server and the user interface on
     different machines, you will almost certainly need to run the
     server with parameter <option>-ORBpoa_iiop_name_port</option>
     as described below.
    </para>
   </warning>
  </refsect1>

  <refsect1>
   <title>Options</title>
   <variablelist>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><option>-ORBInitialHost</option> <replaceable>host</replaceable>
      (default = <literal>localhost</literal>)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       Specifies that the &corba; naming service is running on
       the machine <replaceable>host</replaceable>.
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><option>-ORBInitialPort</option> <replaceable>port</replaceable>
      (default = <literal>8088</literal>)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       Specifies that the &corba; naming service is listening
       on port <replaceable>port</replaceable> on the given host.
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
    <varlistentry>
     <term><option>-ORBpoa_iiop_name_port</option>
      <replaceable>host</replaceable></term>
     <term><option>-ORBpoa_iiop_name_port</option>
      <replaceable>host</replaceable><option>:</option><replaceable>port</replaceable>
      (default = <literal>localhost</literal>, automatically assigned
      port)</term>
     <listitem>
      <para>
       Specifies that this server is running on the machine
       <replaceable>host</replaceable> (and, if specified, listening on port
       <replaceable>port</replaceable> for connections).
      </para>
      <para>
       Use the <replaceable>host</replaceable> parameter to tell the
       naming service the full IP address of the machine on which this
       server is running, so that this information can be correctly
       given out to clients (such as the user interface).  If the
       default value <literal>localhost</literal> is used, a client
       running on a different machine will be unable to locate this
       server.
      </para>
      <para>
       Use the additional <replaceable>port</replaceable> option if you
       wish to force this server to listen for connections on a particular
       port.  By default the port will be automatically assigned by the
       <acronym>ORB</acronym> and this value will be passed on to the
       naming service.
      </para>
      <para>
       You should only need to use this option if this server is running
       on a different machine from the user interface.
      </para>
     </listitem>
    </varlistentry>
   </variablelist>
  </refsect1>

